1
00:00:51,970 --> 00:00:54,256
(HORSE TROTTING)

2
00:01:30,467 --> 00:01:32,753
(BELL RINGING)

3
00:01:54,032 --> 00:01:55,488
Mr. Blackwood?

4
00:01:59,287 --> 00:02:00,618
Sir?

5
00:02:04,709 --> 00:02:06,916
(GLASS SHATTERING)

6
00:02:09,464 --> 00:02:12,376
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

7
00:02:31,236 --> 00:02:33,568
Mr...

8
00:02:33,655 --> 00:02:37,568
Mr. Blackwood, I'm
sorry. You did ring, sir?

9
00:02:38,243 --> 00:02:39,232
BLACKWOOD: Come down.

10
00:03:00,932 --> 00:03:02,263
(SCREAMS)

11
00:03:11,902 --> 00:03:13,608
<i>(WHEN YOU AND I WERE YOUNG,
MAGGIE PLAYING)</i>

12
00:03:13,695 --> 00:03:17,233
<i># I wandered today
to the hill, Maggie</i>

13
00:03:19,367 --> 00:03:21,107
(GROANING)

14
00:03:22,162 --> 00:03:25,529
<i># The creek and the creaking
old mill, Maggie</i>

15
00:03:25,624 --> 00:03:26,909
I'm so...

16
00:03:27,083 --> 00:03:29,745
So very sorry.

17
00:03:30,879 --> 00:03:32,710
I didn't see the steps.

18
00:03:32,797 --> 00:03:34,128
They made me do it.

19
00:03:34,382 --> 00:03:35,417
I didn't...

20
00:03:37,802 --> 00:03:39,133
(GRUNTS)

21
00:03:39,763 --> 00:03:41,970
If I want to see
my child again,

22
00:03:43,308 --> 00:03:44,423
I must comply.

23
00:03:44,517 --> 00:03:45,632
Mr. Blackwood.

24
00:03:45,727 --> 00:03:47,092
Please understand.

25
00:03:49,981 --> 00:03:51,016
(GASPS)

26
00:03:52,192 --> 00:03:53,477
(WHIMPERS)

27
00:03:54,152 --> 00:03:55,141
(SCREAMING)

28
00:04:02,702 --> 00:04:03,737
(MUFFLED SCREAMS)

29
00:04:09,793 --> 00:04:15,208
<i># ...are gone, Maggie
When you and I...</i>

30
00:04:16,174 --> 00:04:18,961
BLACKWOOD: Precious
teeth. Beautiful teeth.

31
00:04:24,182 --> 00:04:25,592
Ransom for my boy.

32
00:04:28,853 --> 00:04:30,013
Yes.

33
00:04:36,903 --> 00:04:41,988
<i># They say I'm feeble
with age, Maggie</i>

34
00:04:43,576 --> 00:04:45,066
BO Y: (FAINTLY) Daddy.

35
00:04:47,414 --> 00:04:52,659
<i># My face is
a well written page, Maggie #</i>

36
00:04:54,170 --> 00:04:55,205
(FAINT WHISPERING)

37
00:04:58,883 --> 00:05:00,999
(SNARLING)

38
00:05:03,972 --> 00:05:07,635
I... I brought you
something more to eat.

39
00:05:09,978 --> 00:05:13,721
Not children's
teeth like you wanted,

40
00:05:14,733 --> 00:05:17,941
but please accept them

41
00:05:18,862 --> 00:05:20,818
in exchange for him.

42
00:05:20,905 --> 00:05:23,647
CREATURES: Children's teeth.

43
00:05:23,742 --> 00:05:26,233
(CREATURES HISSING)

44
00:05:26,328 --> 00:05:28,660
Oh, no, that's the best I could do.

45
00:05:28,830 --> 00:05:31,993
And they're my own.
You see?

46
00:05:32,751 --> 00:05:33,911
My own.

47
00:05:34,586 --> 00:05:38,249
(SOBBING) Please.
Give me back my son!

48
00:05:38,465 --> 00:05:42,834
CREATURES: Yes, your son
is down here. Reach for him.

49
00:05:43,053 --> 00:05:45,339
Son? Son!

50
00:05:45,430 --> 00:05:46,920
(BO Y FAINTLY CALLING)

51
00:05:47,057 --> 00:05:48,046
Son!

52
00:05:49,017 --> 00:05:50,097
Grab my hand!

53
00:05:51,478 --> 00:05:52,763
(CREATURES SHRIEKING)

54
00:05:53,063 --> 00:05:55,600
(SCREAMING)

55
00:07:42,088 --> 00:07:44,044
(INTERCOM BEEPS)

56
00:07:44,132 --> 00:07:46,839
<i>FEMALE FLIGHT ATTENDANT: We've now begun
our descent into T.F. Green Airport.</i>

57
00:07:47,010 --> 00:07:49,046
<i>Please return to your seat,
make sure it is in...</i>

58
00:07:49,179 --> 00:07:51,215
(CART BEEPING)

59
00:07:59,856 --> 00:08:00,891
She's landed.

60
00:08:02,400 --> 00:08:04,265
What do you think?
Too much?

61
00:08:04,360 --> 00:08:07,022
No, it's perfect.
Just like you.

62
00:08:07,113 --> 00:08:08,774
(CART HONKS)

63
00:08:09,073 --> 00:08:10,188
There's my girl.

64
00:08:11,326 --> 00:08:12,315
Sally?

65
00:08:13,203 --> 00:08:16,286
Wow! Look
how tall you are!

66
00:08:17,081 --> 00:08:18,287
What are you,
17 now?

67
00:08:18,374 --> 00:08:20,330
Dad, you know
how old I am.

68
00:08:20,418 --> 00:08:21,783
I know.
I'm being silly.

69
00:08:22,128 --> 00:08:23,413
- Hey.
- Good morning, sir.

70
00:08:24,422 --> 00:08:25,628
Thank you.

71
00:08:25,757 --> 00:08:26,837
ALEX: Come on.

72
00:08:27,550 --> 00:08:29,916
Sally, this is Kim.
Kim, Sally.

73
00:08:30,678 --> 00:08:32,509
Hi, Sally.
It's nice to meet you.

74
00:08:34,390 --> 00:08:36,676
<i>TO Y BEAR: I love you.
I love you.</i>

75
00:08:37,268 --> 00:08:38,257
Thanks.

76
00:08:39,103 --> 00:08:41,515
What about a picture?
You got your camera?

77
00:08:42,732 --> 00:08:44,063
It's good
to see you.

78
00:08:47,237 --> 00:08:48,602
(CAMERA SHUTTER CLICKS)

79
00:08:50,615 --> 00:08:52,776
<i>MAN ON RADIO: Good morning,
Rhode Island!</i>

80
00:08:52,951 --> 00:08:54,782
KIM: Everything okay?
ALEX: Yeah.

81
00:08:55,036 --> 00:08:58,073
<i>We've got fog this morning
and a slight chance of a shower later on.</i>

82
00:08:58,248 --> 00:08:59,488
Smell that fresh air,
kiddo?

83
00:08:59,749 --> 00:09:01,455
- Sure beats the smog of LA, huh?
- (WATCH ALARM RINGS)

84
00:09:10,677 --> 00:09:12,588
(DIALING PHONE)

85
00:09:12,804 --> 00:09:13,884
I have to call
Mom now.

86
00:09:14,806 --> 00:09:17,468
Just press one
and the green.

87
00:09:17,809 --> 00:09:20,175
(PHONE RINGING)

88
00:09:21,646 --> 00:09:26,106
<i>Hi, you've called Joanne
and the magical Sally! Leave us a message.</i>

89
00:10:02,854 --> 00:10:04,685
L.C. delivered
the flooring.

90
00:10:04,772 --> 00:10:06,854
If it rains, I'm afraid
it's going to warp.

91
00:10:07,025 --> 00:10:08,936
Well, just put it
in the garage.

92
00:10:09,360 --> 00:10:11,225
Sally, say hello
to Mr. Harris.

93
00:10:13,990 --> 00:10:15,355
Nice to meet you.

94
00:10:17,952 --> 00:10:20,193
ALEX: Come take
a look at the house.

95
00:10:24,000 --> 00:10:28,164
MRS. UNDERHILL: Mr. Harris. Mr.
Harris, would you give me a hand...

96
00:10:31,883 --> 00:10:34,465
KIM: How's it going?
- Good.

97
00:10:35,553 --> 00:10:38,966
- When do you think you'll be finished?
- No problem.

98
00:11:08,378 --> 00:11:09,538
Good, huh?

99
00:11:13,091 --> 00:11:15,423
- It smells funny.
- Oh, you should have smelled it before.

100
00:11:15,510 --> 00:11:17,466
They had moldy
newspapers everywhere,

101
00:11:17,553 --> 00:11:19,544
and dead pigeons all
over the floor and poop.

102
00:11:19,639 --> 00:11:20,674
(PHONE RINGING)

103
00:11:20,765 --> 00:11:22,255
- Lots of it.
- It's Jacoby's office.

104
00:11:22,892 --> 00:11:24,098
Mr. Jacoby.

105
00:11:24,268 --> 00:11:26,054
Oh, hey, Michelle.
Sorry.

106
00:11:28,231 --> 00:11:30,973
Uh, I don't know.
Hold on. I'll check.

107
00:11:31,067 --> 00:11:32,773
You got
the photographs?

108
00:11:55,049 --> 00:11:56,585
I like to draw, too.

109
00:12:01,764 --> 00:12:02,924
You work here?

110
00:12:04,058 --> 00:12:05,719
No, Sally,
I live here.

111
00:12:06,477 --> 00:12:09,594
I'm the interior designer.
Do you know what that is?

112
00:12:10,273 --> 00:12:11,604
Of course you do.

113
00:12:13,776 --> 00:12:16,392
You see all the animal
paintings and friezes?

114
00:12:16,487 --> 00:12:19,650
They're by Emerson Blackwood,
a man who once lived here.

115
00:12:20,408 --> 00:12:22,740
He was a very
famous wildlife painter.

116
00:12:25,037 --> 00:12:26,447
Hey, Sally, look.

117
00:12:29,292 --> 00:12:30,623
You want to try?

118
00:12:32,795 --> 00:12:34,126
What do you
have there?

119
00:12:35,339 --> 00:12:37,455
- I found it.
- That's mine.

120
00:12:39,927 --> 00:12:43,294
It was my grandmother's. When I
was little, my mother gave it to me.

121
00:12:44,265 --> 00:12:45,630
My mom gave me
to my dad.

122
00:12:46,434 --> 00:12:47,469
ALEX: Sally?

123
00:12:47,769 --> 00:12:49,680
You want to see
your room?

124
00:13:14,378 --> 00:13:15,709
What do you think?

125
00:13:16,881 --> 00:13:19,463
Kim and I worked really
hard to get it ready.

126
00:13:19,550 --> 00:13:21,211
Check this out.

127
00:13:23,054 --> 00:13:25,636
(LULLAB Y PLAYING)

128
00:13:25,723 --> 00:13:27,054
It's pretty great, huh?

129
00:13:29,727 --> 00:13:31,558
It looks better
at night.

130
00:13:36,067 --> 00:13:37,307
How long am
I staying here?

131
00:13:39,320 --> 00:13:41,276
What did your
mother tell you?

132
00:13:41,572 --> 00:13:43,483
She told me I was
coming to visit.

133
00:13:43,616 --> 00:13:45,527
But then she packed
all my clothes.

134
00:13:46,577 --> 00:13:47,862
She didn't explain
anything to you?

135
00:13:49,080 --> 00:13:50,661
- No.
- Sally.

136
00:13:50,832 --> 00:13:52,413
Your mother and I
are worried about you.

137
00:13:52,708 --> 00:13:56,200
She thinks that maybe
you're feeling sad

138
00:13:56,587 --> 00:14:00,580
and she thought that... Well,
we thought that perhaps a change

139
00:14:00,675 --> 00:14:02,381
might be good for you
and that you could come

140
00:14:02,468 --> 00:14:04,459
and live here
with Kim and me

141
00:14:04,554 --> 00:14:07,136
until we finish the work
on the house and sell it.

142
00:14:07,223 --> 00:14:09,680
Then we could move
somewhere else and...

143
00:14:12,228 --> 00:14:14,014
Sally? Come on.
Open the door.

144
00:14:17,859 --> 00:14:19,190
Come on.
Let me in.

145
00:14:21,737 --> 00:14:23,022
(SOBBING) Are you going to marry her?

146
00:14:23,781 --> 00:14:24,770
(CHUCKLES)

147
00:14:26,868 --> 00:14:28,779
Uh, that's between
Kim and me.

148
00:14:28,953 --> 00:14:32,116
Mom said you only liked
her because she was young.

149
00:14:33,291 --> 00:14:35,873
But she isn't.
She's old.

150
00:14:36,294 --> 00:14:37,534
Sally.

151
00:14:38,045 --> 00:14:39,501
Open the door.

152
00:14:39,589 --> 00:14:41,705
Come on, sweetheart.
Open the door.

153
00:14:41,841 --> 00:14:44,002
Sally, please,
let's talk about this.

154
00:14:48,639 --> 00:14:49,970
Look, I know...

155
00:14:54,145 --> 00:14:55,476
I know it must
be tough.

156
00:14:55,563 --> 00:14:59,522
You've had a long flight, and
it's strange being in a new house.

157
00:14:59,609 --> 00:15:01,190
I want to go
to bed now.

158
00:15:04,655 --> 00:15:05,644
Okay.

159
00:15:12,955 --> 00:15:15,196
Don't forget to
brush your teeth.

160
00:15:33,517 --> 00:15:35,257
You'd be a terrible
poker player.

161
00:15:35,436 --> 00:15:37,802
You've been ironing that
shirt for half-an-hour.

162
00:15:41,525 --> 00:15:43,311
She sure didn't
take to me.

163
00:15:44,528 --> 00:15:45,563
I wouldn't take
it personally.

164
00:15:45,655 --> 00:15:47,236
She's like that
with everybody.

165
00:15:47,323 --> 00:15:49,564
Those pills she takes,
what are they?

166
00:15:50,034 --> 00:15:51,194
Adderall, I think.

167
00:15:51,869 --> 00:15:53,029
Jesus.

168
00:15:53,204 --> 00:15:54,319
That's her mother
for you.

169
00:15:55,206 --> 00:15:57,037
That woman medicated
our dogs.

170
00:15:58,292 --> 00:15:59,281
(SOFT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO)

171
00:16:00,711 --> 00:16:03,828
So, what about Jacoby?

172
00:16:04,799 --> 00:16:07,916
His assistant said he still hasn't
looked at the new photographs yet.

173
00:16:08,052 --> 00:16:09,383
- He's had them for a week.
- I know.

174
00:16:09,470 --> 00:16:11,756
We're still in the running, and
he's still coming to the dinner.

175
00:16:11,889 --> 00:16:13,629
- He should just give us the cover.
- Yes, he should.

176
00:16:13,724 --> 00:16:15,806
He gave it to the Spencer
restoration two years ago

177
00:16:15,893 --> 00:16:17,804
and you have
done miracles here.

178
00:16:17,979 --> 00:16:21,187
We have done miracles here.
It's not all about me.

179
00:16:23,567 --> 00:16:24,682
Thank you.

180
00:16:26,153 --> 00:16:27,313
These are new?

181
00:16:27,488 --> 00:16:28,603
- Yeah.
- Great.

182
00:16:28,990 --> 00:16:30,730
<i>If we get the cover of
Architectural Digest,</i>

183
00:16:30,825 --> 00:16:33,407
we won't need to take out
another bank loan, will we?

184
00:16:37,248 --> 00:16:39,204
You know what your
daughter told me today?

185
00:16:39,375 --> 00:16:40,364
What?

186
00:16:41,085 --> 00:16:43,326
She said your
wife gave her to you.

187
00:16:46,841 --> 00:16:49,583
Kids say all kinds of
things they don't mean.

188
00:16:53,431 --> 00:16:55,422
It couldn't have
gone any worse today.

189
00:16:56,350 --> 00:16:57,339
(SIGHS)

190
00:16:57,435 --> 00:16:59,551
I feel like
the evil stepmother.

191
00:17:00,229 --> 00:17:02,641
The evil and
very old stepmother.

192
00:17:02,773 --> 00:17:04,138
- Let's not forget the old part.
- (LAUGHING)

193
00:17:05,109 --> 00:17:08,601
Because I was kind of thinking
you were looking a little ancient.

194
00:17:08,696 --> 00:17:10,106
KIM: Oh, yeah?
- Oh, yeah.

195
00:17:10,364 --> 00:17:11,945
The stuffed bear?
What was I thinking?

196
00:17:12,116 --> 00:17:14,653
Oh, come on. It's great. She
likes it. I saw it in her room.

197
00:17:14,744 --> 00:17:16,075
KIM: On her bed?

198
00:17:16,245 --> 00:17:19,203
- Well, above the bed. Hanging by a noose.
- (KIM CHUCKLES)

199
00:17:20,082 --> 00:17:22,368
That's okay. Nice sign
of affection, I think.

200
00:17:22,460 --> 00:17:25,452
(KIM'S LAUGH ECHOING)

201
00:17:27,089 --> 00:17:28,545
(LULLAB Y PLAYING)

202
00:17:39,477 --> 00:17:41,138
(SIGHS)

203
00:18:14,386 --> 00:18:19,471
CREATURES: (WHISPERING) Sally.
Her name is Sally.

204
00:18:25,189 --> 00:18:27,680
(HUMMING)

205
00:18:44,208 --> 00:18:45,197
Sally!

206
00:20:01,535 --> 00:20:02,866
(GASPS)

207
00:20:32,733 --> 00:20:33,722
KIM: What do you think?

208
00:20:34,485 --> 00:20:35,816
Yeah. Looks great.

209
00:20:37,446 --> 00:20:38,652
Have you seen Sally?

210
00:20:38,781 --> 00:20:39,987
Yeah, she's
on the bench.

211
00:20:42,451 --> 00:20:43,611
ALEX: Sally!

212
00:21:48,100 --> 00:21:50,386
(SCREAMING)

213
00:21:51,270 --> 00:21:53,010
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

214
00:21:54,315 --> 00:21:56,897
It is not safe
for you back here.

215
00:21:57,860 --> 00:22:00,317
Hey. What's going on?
Everything okay?

216
00:22:00,404 --> 00:22:02,110
Keep her out from
the back of the house.

217
00:22:02,197 --> 00:22:04,483
She could fall in. We'd
be in a hell of a mess.

218
00:22:04,575 --> 00:22:06,361
I didn't do anything.

219
00:22:06,535 --> 00:22:08,651
There's pits.
Old wells.

220
00:22:08,746 --> 00:22:10,202
It's dangerous
for a child.

221
00:22:10,289 --> 00:22:11,745
Mr. Harris is right,
Sally. He knows.

222
00:22:11,874 --> 00:22:13,239
His grandfather
worked at the house.

223
00:22:13,375 --> 00:22:15,331
- You shouldn't be back here.
- But I found a basement.

224
00:22:15,419 --> 00:22:16,875
There is no basement.

225
00:22:17,046 --> 00:22:18,877
Easy, Harris. I'll take her. It's okay.

226
00:22:20,758 --> 00:22:23,420
It's there!
It's right there!

227
00:22:27,431 --> 00:22:30,969
There's a reason this
house is called Fallen Mill.

228
00:22:31,060 --> 00:22:32,220
The English had
a mill here,

229
00:22:32,311 --> 00:22:33,676
and it fell
into a sinkhole.

230
00:22:33,771 --> 00:22:36,262
That's why most of the houses
around here don't have basements.

231
00:22:36,357 --> 00:22:37,517
This one does.

232
00:22:37,608 --> 00:22:39,269
ALEX: You may want
to check this out.

233
00:22:39,360 --> 00:22:40,600
HARRIS: It's unsafe
for a child.

234
00:22:40,694 --> 00:22:41,729
Pull on that.

235
00:22:42,112 --> 00:22:43,477
(ALEX LAUGHS)

236
00:22:43,572 --> 00:22:45,608
SALLY: Look! I told you it was here!

237
00:22:45,699 --> 00:22:47,030
ALEX: Can you believe this?

238
00:22:51,205 --> 00:22:52,615
(KNOCKING)

239
00:22:53,957 --> 00:22:55,538
This is
definitely hollow.

240
00:22:57,252 --> 00:22:58,583
I'm going to
get some tools.

241
00:23:03,300 --> 00:23:04,631
You sure you want
to do this now?

242
00:23:04,760 --> 00:23:06,045
Of course!
You kidding?

243
00:23:06,136 --> 00:23:08,468
We can fix this
easy if we have to.

244
00:23:08,555 --> 00:23:10,671
You may want
to step back.

245
00:23:11,600 --> 00:23:13,966
(HAMMERING)

246
00:23:14,645 --> 00:23:15,976
HARRIS: Mr. Hurst, I...

247
00:23:19,316 --> 00:23:21,557
(ALEX GRUNTING)

248
00:23:33,831 --> 00:23:35,162
There's a door in here.

249
00:23:40,003 --> 00:23:41,288
Where did you put
the old house keys?

250
00:23:41,380 --> 00:23:44,167
They're in your junk
drawer in the office.

251
00:23:44,299 --> 00:23:45,334
Okay.

252
00:23:46,343 --> 00:23:47,674
Have a look.

253
00:24:17,374 --> 00:24:18,864
ALEX: Oh, wow.

254
00:24:19,543 --> 00:24:21,704
- You be careful, Sally. Okay?
- Okay.

255
00:24:24,715 --> 00:24:27,081
How the hell did
we miss this?

256
00:24:32,473 --> 00:24:34,134
KIM: That must be
the garden window.

257
00:24:43,150 --> 00:24:46,813
KIM: It's all of his paints and old
colored pencils. This is amazing.

258
00:25:02,753 --> 00:25:05,165
Wow. Alex,
look at this.

259
00:25:13,597 --> 00:25:15,007
Harris, did you know
about this?

260
00:25:15,098 --> 00:25:17,339
This place isn't safe.
(STAMMERS)

261
00:25:17,434 --> 00:25:18,970
Especially for kids.

262
00:25:19,061 --> 00:25:20,551
It's okay. I'll keep
an eye on her.

263
00:25:22,689 --> 00:25:24,600
This must be where
Blackwood worked.

264
00:25:24,691 --> 00:25:25,897
SALLY: I found
another door.

265
00:25:26,568 --> 00:25:27,808
KIM: Look at
these sketches.

266
00:25:27,945 --> 00:25:29,230
It's an ash pit,
I think.

267
00:25:30,113 --> 00:25:32,354
Yeah. It's bolted shut.

268
00:25:33,033 --> 00:25:34,443
KIM: These are incredible.

269
00:25:38,956 --> 00:25:40,571
(GASPS)

270
00:25:41,041 --> 00:25:42,622
ALEX: Okay.
Let's go, Sally.

271
00:25:53,804 --> 00:25:55,135
Come on, Sally.
Let's go.

272
00:25:56,473 --> 00:25:57,462
ALEX: Sally, come on.

273
00:25:59,476 --> 00:26:01,637
This must be like
King Tut's tomb for you.

274
00:26:01,812 --> 00:26:04,178
KIM: Which is why we
shouldn't be touching anything.

275
00:26:04,273 --> 00:26:05,729
This stuff must
be valuable.

276
00:26:05,816 --> 00:26:07,352
CREATURES: (HISSING)
She's gone.

277
00:26:07,484 --> 00:26:09,065
No, no, she will come back.

278
00:26:09,236 --> 00:26:11,067
They always do.

279
00:26:11,154 --> 00:26:13,611
Yes, they always do.

280
00:26:49,860 --> 00:26:51,521
ALEX: I don't think
that's important, Alan.

281
00:26:53,363 --> 00:26:54,944
No, I just need
to make sure I get

282
00:26:55,032 --> 00:26:57,523
the paintings and furniture
back in time for the dinner.

283
00:26:58,368 --> 00:26:59,699
You told me
you could.

284
00:27:01,538 --> 00:27:02,994
Come on. How long
have we known each other?

285
00:27:03,081 --> 00:27:04,992
I'll write you
a post-dated check.

286
00:27:07,544 --> 00:27:08,954
Hold on.

287
00:27:09,671 --> 00:27:14,461
It's either walnut or
mahogany, I think. Yeah.

288
00:27:15,469 --> 00:27:19,462
There you are. I thought
maybe we could bake scones.

289
00:27:20,223 --> 00:27:23,807
I promised Mrs. Underhill we
wouldn't make too much of a mess.

290
00:27:23,894 --> 00:27:25,225
No. That's all right.

291
00:27:26,980 --> 00:27:29,141
What have you got there?

292
00:27:30,692 --> 00:27:33,229
My doll.
And my drawing stuff.

293
00:27:40,077 --> 00:27:43,035
KIM: Looks like it's just
you and I baking scones today.

294
00:27:50,295 --> 00:27:52,411
MRS. UNDERHILL: I made
sandwiches for everyone.

295
00:28:21,368 --> 00:28:23,609
(GRUNTING)

296
00:28:35,590 --> 00:28:37,000
CREATURES: (WHISPERING)
Sally.

297
00:28:37,551 --> 00:28:39,337
Open the grates!

298
00:28:39,469 --> 00:28:41,209
Yes, yes,
open the grates.

299
00:28:41,304 --> 00:28:44,467
Set us free!
Set us free!

300
00:28:48,812 --> 00:28:50,143
Who are you?

301
00:28:51,440 --> 00:28:52,771
What do you look like?

302
00:28:53,191 --> 00:28:56,274
We've been locked
up for so long.

303
00:28:56,361 --> 00:28:58,147
Set us free!

304
00:28:59,823 --> 00:29:00,812
(GASPS)

305
00:29:02,159 --> 00:29:05,447
Come down. You'll see
what it's like down here.

306
00:29:05,912 --> 00:29:07,118
Wait a minute,
will ya?

307
00:29:07,247 --> 00:29:12,207
There's other children down
here. They're just like you.

308
00:29:13,754 --> 00:29:14,994
ALEX: Sally?

309
00:29:19,676 --> 00:29:20,665
Sally.

310
00:29:22,846 --> 00:29:24,461
What are you
doing down here?

311
00:29:26,600 --> 00:29:29,592
- I heard something.
- Rats, probably. It's time for dinner.

312
00:29:30,270 --> 00:29:31,350
It was a voice.

313
00:29:31,521 --> 00:29:32,601
Really smart rats, then.

314
00:29:32,689 --> 00:29:34,270
No! Listen.

315
00:29:50,707 --> 00:29:53,039
Nothing. Come on.
Let's go, kiddo.

316
00:30:07,724 --> 00:30:08,930
I forgot my bag.

317
00:30:09,059 --> 00:30:10,299
Hurry it up, then.

318
00:30:27,244 --> 00:30:28,984
(CLANKING)

319
00:30:37,587 --> 00:30:39,327
(GASPS)

320
00:30:39,422 --> 00:30:40,832
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

321
00:31:29,222 --> 00:31:30,553
ALEX: Sally, now!

322
00:32:06,760 --> 00:32:09,251
We can get this tomorrow. We can't
get the rest of these for two weeks.

323
00:32:09,346 --> 00:32:10,961
What about
the burnt umber?

324
00:32:11,139 --> 00:32:14,347
It's much warmer, and we can
get it for half the price.

325
00:32:15,060 --> 00:32:17,051
You not hungry?
Sally?

326
00:32:19,940 --> 00:32:21,271
Don't you like rice?

327
00:32:22,442 --> 00:32:25,479
Mrs. Underhill made
apple pie for dessert.

328
00:32:25,695 --> 00:32:27,231
Apple pie has gluten,

329
00:32:27,322 --> 00:32:29,028
and Mommy says gluten is
bad for my concentration.

330
00:32:29,115 --> 00:32:31,151
Oh, come on.
You love apple pie.

331
00:32:31,242 --> 00:32:33,858
We can worry about your
concentration tomorrow.

332
00:32:33,954 --> 00:32:35,694
Mommy says
no gluten.

333
00:32:36,289 --> 00:32:37,699
What's your mother
filling your head with?

334
00:32:37,791 --> 00:32:39,281
- How about some chocolate milk?
- No.

335
00:32:39,376 --> 00:32:40,786
- I'll make something else.
- Hold on.

336
00:32:40,877 --> 00:32:41,957
Sally, you need
to eat this,

337
00:32:42,045 --> 00:32:43,785
or you can go to your room. Okay?

338
00:32:45,548 --> 00:32:47,334
Good night, Dad.

339
00:32:54,683 --> 00:32:55,763
What?

340
00:32:56,685 --> 00:32:59,097
- Did that work on you when you were a kid?
- She's testing us, Kim.

341
00:32:59,187 --> 00:33:01,849
That's what kids do.
Who's the parent here?

342
00:33:02,023 --> 00:33:03,684
Certainly not me.

343
00:33:03,858 --> 00:33:05,314
I didn't mean that.

344
00:33:05,485 --> 00:33:08,397
No. You're right.
I'm not a parent.

345
00:33:08,571 --> 00:33:12,280
- We talked about this, remember?
- No, you told me about this, Alex.

346
00:33:12,450 --> 00:33:15,613
I'm not sure I'm ready
to be anybody's mother.

347
00:33:15,787 --> 00:33:18,199
I had a hard enough time
getting over my own childhood

348
00:33:18,289 --> 00:33:20,075
to have to deal
with somebody else's.

349
00:33:20,166 --> 00:33:21,827
Listen, will you help
me with this, please?

350
00:33:21,918 --> 00:33:24,375
I realize this is terrible
timing, but I don't have a choice.

351
00:33:24,462 --> 00:33:26,168
I can't just
send her back.

352
00:33:29,009 --> 00:33:31,045
That's not what
I'm asking you to do.

353
00:33:38,518 --> 00:33:39,849
Apple pie.

354
00:33:40,645 --> 00:33:41,680
Thanks.

355
00:33:51,573 --> 00:33:53,029
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

356
00:33:55,702 --> 00:33:57,863
<i>- Hello?
- Hi, Alex. It's Joanne.</i>

357
00:33:58,038 --> 00:33:59,494
<i>- Hi, Joanne.
- Can I speak to Sally?</i>

358
00:33:59,664 --> 00:34:01,120
<i>- No, you can't.
- Why not?</i>

359
00:34:01,291 --> 00:34:03,953
Because she's asleep. We're
three hours ahead, remember?

360
00:34:04,044 --> 00:34:05,750
What were you thinking
not telling her

361
00:34:05,837 --> 00:34:07,702
she was going to
be living here?

362
00:34:12,927 --> 00:34:16,715
You and I had a conversation. I asked
you if you wanted me to tell her.

363
00:34:16,806 --> 00:34:18,216
<i>Don't do this
every time I have...</i>

364
00:34:18,308 --> 00:34:19,639
You're the one
who wanted her here.

365
00:34:29,819 --> 00:34:31,309
(GASPS)

366
00:35:10,026 --> 00:35:12,108
(LULLABY PLAYING)

367
00:35:16,658 --> 00:35:19,570
<i>TOY BEAR: I love you. I love you.
- (GASPS)</i>

368
00:35:26,876 --> 00:35:30,368
Did you just
speak to me?

369
00:35:30,547 --> 00:35:33,960
<i>I love you.
I love you.</i>

370
00:35:35,385 --> 00:35:37,000
<i>I love you.</i>

371
00:35:37,971 --> 00:35:39,302
<i>I love you.</i>

372
00:35:41,057 --> 00:35:42,422
<i>I love you.</i>

373
00:35:44,227 --> 00:35:45,558
<i>I love you.</i>

374
00:35:51,234 --> 00:35:52,940
(SCREAMS)

375
00:35:53,903 --> 00:35:55,689
(CREATURES SHRIEKING)

376
00:35:55,780 --> 00:35:57,896
CREATURES: The light,
it hurts us.

377
00:35:58,032 --> 00:35:59,442
Yeah. Turn out the light.

378
00:36:01,161 --> 00:36:02,492
<i>I love you.</i>

379
00:36:03,413 --> 00:36:05,825
(CREATURES WHISPERING)

380
00:36:05,915 --> 00:36:07,530
Turn out the light.

381
00:36:08,418 --> 00:36:10,750
We want to be friends.

382
00:36:16,718 --> 00:36:18,049
Where's my doll?

383
00:36:18,178 --> 00:36:21,545
CREATURES: (WHISPERING) With
us. Sally's doll is with us.

384
00:36:23,308 --> 00:36:24,764
Who are you?

385
00:36:25,059 --> 00:36:26,970
We're your friends.

386
00:36:30,190 --> 00:36:31,521
Friends?

387
00:36:33,484 --> 00:36:34,473
Where?

388
00:36:34,777 --> 00:36:37,519
CREATURES: (WHISPERING) Come down
to the basement and play with us.

389
00:36:37,614 --> 00:36:38,945
Where are you?

390
00:36:55,590 --> 00:36:56,921
What are you?

391
00:37:06,351 --> 00:37:07,466
CREATURES: Hungry.

392
00:37:08,144 --> 00:37:09,133
Hungry.

393
00:37:10,146 --> 00:37:11,511
Very hungry.

394
00:37:13,441 --> 00:37:15,147
(WHISPERS)
I have food.

395
00:37:21,908 --> 00:37:23,364
Let me see you.

396
00:37:24,535 --> 00:37:26,526
I won't hurt you,
I promise.

397
00:37:28,665 --> 00:37:29,654
ALEX: Sally?

398
00:37:31,501 --> 00:37:34,334
- What are you doing under there?
- I'm looking for my doll.

399
00:37:34,420 --> 00:37:35,751
Looking for what?

400
00:37:35,838 --> 00:37:37,078
I'm looking
for my doll.

401
00:37:37,757 --> 00:37:38,746
ALEX: Oh.

402
00:37:43,763 --> 00:37:46,004
How about
Teddy instead?

403
00:37:46,182 --> 00:37:48,844
No. That's all right.

404
00:37:51,854 --> 00:37:53,810
- Did you lose a tooth?
- That's not mine.

405
00:37:54,607 --> 00:37:57,269
- I found it.
- You found it? Here in the house?

406
00:37:58,820 --> 00:38:00,151
Yeah.

407
00:38:02,615 --> 00:38:04,071
Can I call Mommy now?

408
00:38:04,242 --> 00:38:06,574
No, it's too late.
She's probably asleep.

409
00:38:06,744 --> 00:38:10,407
I don't think you should keep
this. It's not very sanitary.

410
00:38:10,873 --> 00:38:12,363
What about this light?
Should I...

411
00:38:13,001 --> 00:38:14,332
Leave it on, please.

412
00:38:14,961 --> 00:38:16,826
All right, well,
sleep well.

413
00:38:20,216 --> 00:38:22,423
Oh, Sally, would you do me a favor?

414
00:38:23,678 --> 00:38:25,794
Would you try to, maybe,
be friends with Kim?

415
00:38:28,433 --> 00:38:30,014
- Yes.
- Thanks, kiddo.

416
00:38:59,922 --> 00:39:01,207
(CLASSICAL MUSIC PLAYING
ON STEREO)

417
00:39:03,593 --> 00:39:05,083
Kim, have you
seen my razor?

418
00:39:06,262 --> 00:39:07,798
We have to leave
in five minutes.

419
00:39:07,805 --> 00:39:10,137
- Yeah. Have you seen my razor?
- Here, take mine.

420
00:39:11,017 --> 00:39:12,097
Five minutes.

421
00:39:24,238 --> 00:39:25,227
My dress.

422
00:39:36,209 --> 00:39:37,745
(HUMMING)

423
00:39:49,055 --> 00:39:52,547
Sally. I want to talk to
you downstairs right now.

424
00:39:56,896 --> 00:39:59,137
ALEX: I cannot believe you
cut up Kim's clothes.

425
00:39:59,232 --> 00:40:00,517
SALLY: (CRYING)
I didn't do it.

426
00:40:00,608 --> 00:40:03,315
- I didn't do anything. I swear.
- Stop lying.

427
00:40:04,112 --> 00:40:06,319
It was a horrible thing to
do. And it was dangerous.

428
00:40:06,406 --> 00:40:07,441
You could have
cut yourself.

429
00:40:07,532 --> 00:40:08,863
What did you use,
my razor?

430
00:40:09,325 --> 00:40:10,531
Let me see
your hands.

431
00:40:11,160 --> 00:40:12,650
- It's mine.
- What is this?

432
00:40:12,745 --> 00:40:14,076
Where did you get this?

433
00:40:15,498 --> 00:40:16,908
- Let me go home.
- You can't go home.

434
00:40:16,999 --> 00:40:18,489
Just let me
go home.

435
00:40:20,086 --> 00:40:21,417
I'm sorry
about this.

436
00:40:21,587 --> 00:40:22,622
She's never done
anything like this before.

437
00:40:23,214 --> 00:40:25,500
She's obviously very
angry about something.

438
00:40:25,591 --> 00:40:28,298
Alex, that is not anger.
That is fear.

439
00:40:28,386 --> 00:40:30,297
We need to go.
Mrs. Underhill,

440
00:40:30,388 --> 00:40:32,470
Kim and I have an appointment
at the historical society.

441
00:40:32,557 --> 00:40:34,218
We'll be back
this afternoon.

442
00:40:34,392 --> 00:40:35,848
Sally, we're going out.

443
00:40:36,519 --> 00:40:38,931
Listen to Mrs. Underhill
and do what she says.

444
00:40:39,021 --> 00:40:41,683
And you think about what
you need to say to Kim, okay?

445
00:40:57,999 --> 00:41:01,491
(FAINT WHISPERING)

446
00:41:08,885 --> 00:41:10,216
Are you there?

447
00:41:21,814 --> 00:41:23,554
Did you cut
Kim's clothes?

448
00:41:30,406 --> 00:41:32,271
Do you have
my dad's razor?

449
00:41:34,827 --> 00:41:36,567
You have to tell
me the truth.

450
00:41:37,997 --> 00:41:39,737
If you want
to be friends.

451
00:41:42,793 --> 00:41:44,124
I won't be angry.

452
00:41:45,588 --> 00:41:47,829
CREATURE 1: (WHISPERING)
Sally's not angry.

453
00:41:48,382 --> 00:41:50,418
CREATURE 1: They're angry.

454
00:41:50,510 --> 00:41:52,967
CREATURE 2:
No, I'm not angry.

455
00:41:53,888 --> 00:41:56,846
CREATURE 1: They don't
want to...

456
00:41:56,933 --> 00:41:57,922
CREATURES: But we do.

457
00:42:00,770 --> 00:42:03,227
CREATURES: Come
down here, Sally.

458
00:42:03,981 --> 00:42:06,848
Come down and play.

459
00:42:11,822 --> 00:42:13,813
(CREATURES SCREECHING)

460
00:42:13,908 --> 00:42:16,024
(HISSING)

461
00:42:18,871 --> 00:42:20,611
You said you
were hungry.

462
00:42:21,290 --> 00:42:23,121
Do you like raisins?

463
00:42:28,756 --> 00:42:30,371
CREATURES: We said
we liked them.

464
00:42:36,055 --> 00:42:38,546
See? Delicious.

465
00:42:39,225 --> 00:42:42,433
Delicious. Yeah.

466
00:42:42,603 --> 00:42:44,969
So delicious.

467
00:42:47,108 --> 00:42:48,723
Did you do
something bad?

468
00:42:50,236 --> 00:42:52,602
You have to answer if
you want to be friends.

469
00:42:52,822 --> 00:42:54,778
CREATURES:
Yes, friend.

470
00:42:55,074 --> 00:42:56,484
Sally?

471
00:42:58,035 --> 00:43:00,242
What are you doing
down here in the dark?

472
00:43:03,374 --> 00:43:05,490
Were you talking
to someone?

473
00:43:07,837 --> 00:43:09,498
Is there someone
here with you?

474
00:43:10,798 --> 00:43:13,460
No. I'm all alone.

475
00:43:14,385 --> 00:43:15,875
There's nobody here.

476
00:43:17,430 --> 00:43:22,766
Why don't you go help
Mrs. Underhill make lunch?

477
00:43:24,895 --> 00:43:26,351
Go on.
Off you go now.

478
00:43:26,522 --> 00:43:29,605
That's right. Up those
steps! Quick as you can, now!

479
00:44:22,370 --> 00:44:23,951
(GRUNTS)

480
00:44:28,459 --> 00:44:30,825
CREATURES: (WHISPERING)
Harris. You old fool.

481
00:44:32,963 --> 00:44:35,124
(CREATURES WHISPERING)

482
00:44:36,258 --> 00:44:39,876
HARRIS: I swear. I
didn't tell them anything!

483
00:44:54,568 --> 00:44:56,650
(SCREAMING)

484
00:45:02,118 --> 00:45:03,107
(HISSING)

485
00:45:06,455 --> 00:45:07,444
(GROANING)

486
00:45:11,877 --> 00:45:12,866
No.

487
00:45:15,464 --> 00:45:16,453
(YELLING)

488
00:45:19,218 --> 00:45:20,958
No, please!

489
00:45:22,555 --> 00:45:23,544
(CREATURES SHRIEKING)

490
00:45:26,809 --> 00:45:27,798
(GROANING)

491
00:45:35,484 --> 00:45:36,473
(SCREECHING)

492
00:45:43,367 --> 00:45:44,698
Get away!

493
00:45:45,453 --> 00:45:48,911
I had an accident!
Call for help!

494
00:45:51,459 --> 00:45:52,448
(COUGHING)

495
00:45:57,965 --> 00:46:00,206
(MOANING)

496
00:46:05,347 --> 00:46:06,336
(GRUNTING)

497
00:46:17,193 --> 00:46:18,182
Oh.

498
00:46:18,944 --> 00:46:20,275
Don't look.

499
00:46:21,489 --> 00:46:22,478
(SOBBING)

500
00:46:26,035 --> 00:46:28,321
MRS. UNDERHILL: I could
hear screams down there.

501
00:46:28,496 --> 00:46:30,202
- Noises.
COP: Did you see anything?

502
00:46:30,289 --> 00:46:31,904
MRS. UNDERHILL: He asked
me to leave the cellar.

503
00:46:32,082 --> 00:46:34,118
It was so dark in there,
he must have stumbled.

504
00:46:34,251 --> 00:46:36,116
- Oh, Mr. Hurst, thank God!
- What happened?

505
00:46:36,212 --> 00:46:38,043
- Are you William Harris' employer?
- Yeah.

506
00:46:38,130 --> 00:46:39,370
There's been
an accident.

507
00:46:39,632 --> 00:46:41,497
Are you okay?
Where's Sally?

508
00:46:41,634 --> 00:46:43,499
I'm sorry.
She saw him.

509
00:46:43,677 --> 00:46:45,713
I tried to cover her eyes,
and I was too late.

510
00:46:45,805 --> 00:46:47,466
- Where is she?
- She's in the garden.

511
00:46:47,640 --> 00:46:48,971
(CRYING)
Oh, I am sorry!

512
00:46:51,560 --> 00:46:52,970
Sally?

513
00:47:11,914 --> 00:47:13,074
Hi.

514
00:47:16,168 --> 00:47:17,499
Are you scared?

515
00:47:20,923 --> 00:47:22,254
Do you want
to talk about it?

516
00:47:25,344 --> 00:47:27,335
Is Mr. Harris
going to die?

517
00:47:29,348 --> 00:47:30,508
No, Sally.

518
00:47:31,684 --> 00:47:33,345
He is going
to be okay.

519
00:47:46,615 --> 00:47:48,151
Can I show you something?

520
00:48:21,567 --> 00:48:23,979
This is my favorite
part of the house.

521
00:48:24,153 --> 00:48:25,734
Blackwood loved nature.

522
00:48:26,947 --> 00:48:30,531
He imported these fish
from Japan. And so did we.

523
00:48:32,161 --> 00:48:33,492
They're called Koi.

524
00:48:34,747 --> 00:48:36,487
They're considered magical.

525
00:48:37,458 --> 00:48:40,450
Badgers can spot them
against the mud at the bottom

526
00:48:40,628 --> 00:48:42,038
because of
their bright colors.

527
00:48:43,130 --> 00:48:46,247
So what makes
them special

528
00:48:46,342 --> 00:48:49,084
is also what makes
them vulnerable.

529
00:48:50,054 --> 00:48:51,635
They have to be tough.

530
00:48:53,474 --> 00:48:54,964
And you, too, Sally.

531
00:48:59,647 --> 00:49:01,512
(CRYING) I didn't
touch your clothes.

532
00:49:04,526 --> 00:49:06,767
I swear to God,
I never touched them!

533
00:49:09,073 --> 00:49:11,280
- I didn't touch them.
- Sally.

534
00:49:11,367 --> 00:49:15,280
I didn't! Didn't cut them, I promise.

535
00:49:15,371 --> 00:49:17,612
I don't care
about my clothes.

536
00:49:23,212 --> 00:49:25,624
ALEX: I can't really tell.
1804, I think.

537
00:49:26,465 --> 00:49:29,127
It's hard to see. The
coin is pretty worn down.

538
00:49:33,722 --> 00:49:35,883
She probably found it
in Blackwood's studio.

539
00:49:36,725 --> 00:49:39,137
ALEX: I don't want her
going down there anymore.

540
00:49:39,228 --> 00:49:42,220
I'm worried about her,
Kim. It's not safe.

541
00:49:50,990 --> 00:49:51,979
(PHONE DIALING)

542
00:49:52,825 --> 00:49:54,531
<i>- Hey. This is Joanne.
- Mommy?</i>

543
00:49:54,702 --> 00:49:57,364
<i>Oh, sweetie, it's you!
How are you?</i>

544
00:49:58,080 --> 00:49:59,490
Can I come home?

545
00:49:59,665 --> 00:50:02,657
<i>You want to come...
The sashimi. Stuart, the sashimi.</i>

546
00:50:02,751 --> 00:50:04,992
<i>- I don't like it here.
- You what?</i>

547
00:50:05,170 --> 00:50:08,037
<i>Honey, don't fret.
It's so beautiful there.</i>

548
00:50:08,132 --> 00:50:09,997
<i>You just need to
get used to it.</i>

549
00:50:10,092 --> 00:50:11,673
But it's cold.

550
00:50:11,844 --> 00:50:14,085
<i>- Honey, what?
- My bed is too big.</i>

551
00:50:14,263 --> 00:50:16,345
<i>- Sweetheart.
- And I think I'm getting sick.</i>

552
00:50:16,432 --> 00:50:18,138
<i>You're not
getting sick.</i>

553
00:50:18,225 --> 00:50:20,591
<i>It will take a little tiny bit
of getting used to,</i>

554
00:50:20,728 --> 00:50:23,060
<i>but you are going
to be so happy there.</i>

555
00:50:23,147 --> 00:50:26,184
<i>Okay? I promise.
You'll get used to it.</i>

556
00:50:27,568 --> 00:50:29,604
<i>I got to go, honey.
Mommy's got to go.</i>

557
00:50:29,778 --> 00:50:32,269
<i>I'll see you soon. Bye!</i>

558
00:50:58,474 --> 00:50:59,463
(LULLAB Y PLAYING)

559
00:51:29,171 --> 00:51:30,160
Kim?

560
00:51:39,973 --> 00:51:41,964
- Don't leave.
- What's wrong?

561
00:51:43,519 --> 00:51:45,180
Even when I'm asleep.

562
00:51:48,524 --> 00:51:50,060
And don't turn
off the lights.

563
00:51:53,028 --> 00:51:54,359
I'll be right here.

564
00:51:56,740 --> 00:51:57,855
Come on.

565
00:52:09,962 --> 00:52:12,374
(THUNDER RUMBLING)

566
00:53:12,608 --> 00:53:14,564
(CREATURES WHISPERING)

567
00:53:16,945 --> 00:53:17,934
(SCREECHING)

568
00:53:22,451 --> 00:53:23,486
Kim?

569
00:53:28,999 --> 00:53:31,411
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

570
00:53:35,297 --> 00:53:37,663
<i>TOY BEAR: I love you.
I love you.</i>

571
00:54:18,507 --> 00:54:20,498
(SHRIEKS)

572
00:54:20,592 --> 00:54:23,334
(SCREAMING)

573
00:54:25,847 --> 00:54:26,836
(GASPING)

574
00:54:27,849 --> 00:54:29,931
(CREATURES SCREECHING)

575
00:54:32,771 --> 00:54:33,760
(SCREAMING)

576
00:54:35,816 --> 00:54:38,398
Daddy! Daddy!

577
00:54:39,236 --> 00:54:40,692
Daddy, please!

578
00:54:41,363 --> 00:54:42,352
Daddy!

579
00:54:43,991 --> 00:54:46,073
Sally,
what's the matter?

580
00:54:46,410 --> 00:54:48,696
(SALLY SOBBING)

581
00:54:52,874 --> 00:54:55,035
I don't want them
to come anymore.

582
00:54:55,127 --> 00:54:56,116
Who, Sally?

583
00:54:57,004 --> 00:54:58,119
The little things.

584
00:54:59,506 --> 00:55:02,043
They live in the basement.
They gave me the silver dollar.

585
00:55:03,093 --> 00:55:04,879
They said they
wanted to be my friend.

586
00:55:05,012 --> 00:55:07,924
But they're
horrible and mean.

587
00:55:08,140 --> 00:55:09,721
Oh, Sally.

588
00:55:10,726 --> 00:55:11,966
You just had
a nightmare.

589
00:55:12,102 --> 00:55:13,387
Don't say that!

590
00:55:14,062 --> 00:55:15,177
It's okay.

591
00:55:15,689 --> 00:55:16,678
(LULLAB Y PLAYING)

592
00:55:17,399 --> 00:55:18,559
My bear.

593
00:55:19,776 --> 00:55:21,607
Look what they
did to my bear.

594
00:55:52,434 --> 00:55:56,894
Your dad tells me art is your
favorite subject. I wish I could draw.

595
00:55:57,814 --> 00:55:59,429
Drawing is easy.

596
00:56:01,109 --> 00:56:03,100
The other kids can't
do feet and hands.

597
00:56:03,820 --> 00:56:07,859
When you say "the other kids," do
you feel they're different from you?

598
00:56:07,949 --> 00:56:09,655
My doctor back
home asked me that.

599
00:56:09,743 --> 00:56:11,449
What was your answer?

600
00:56:14,956 --> 00:56:18,790
Okay. Let's start
with something easier.

601
00:56:19,920 --> 00:56:21,456
What's your
favorite color?

602
00:56:23,298 --> 00:56:24,629
What is that? Purple?

603
00:56:25,300 --> 00:56:26,289
Black.

604
00:56:28,136 --> 00:56:32,095
How about these little things you
saw? What do you think they are?

605
00:56:39,231 --> 00:56:40,562
Fairies.

606
00:56:42,150 --> 00:56:43,515
Or gnomes.

607
00:56:43,693 --> 00:56:44,853
But scary ones?

608
00:56:48,115 --> 00:56:49,821
And you say they
know your name?

609
00:56:55,664 --> 00:56:56,824
They talk to you?

610
00:56:58,208 --> 00:56:59,197
Yes.

611
00:57:03,004 --> 00:57:04,335
What do they say?

612
00:57:06,174 --> 00:57:07,664
They want to play
with me.

613
00:57:08,218 --> 00:57:09,549
Is that all?

614
00:57:14,474 --> 00:57:16,510
They say my parents
don't love me.

615
00:57:20,522 --> 00:57:22,058
Can I go now?

616
00:57:22,232 --> 00:57:24,063
<i>PSYCHIATRIST: Just a few
more questions, okay?</i>

617
00:57:42,544 --> 00:57:45,035
<i>There is a lot of anxiety in
that little girl</i>

618
00:57:45,172 --> 00:57:47,663
<i>and a deep belief
that she's not wanted.</i>

619
00:57:47,799 --> 00:57:51,383
I believe that's what's triggering
these fantastic episodes.

620
00:57:51,595 --> 00:57:53,381
She told me she
found a little tray

621
00:57:53,472 --> 00:57:55,383
filled with teeth right
inside that fireplace.

622
00:57:55,557 --> 00:57:58,924
Yeah. She found a tooth, but that
doesn't mean anything, does it?

623
00:57:59,227 --> 00:58:01,434
She's constructing
this elaborate fantasy

624
00:58:01,521 --> 00:58:04,228
about wrinkles,
claws, fangs.

625
00:58:04,316 --> 00:58:06,898
She's individuated
each one of those things,

626
00:58:07,068 --> 00:58:08,899
her imaginary world,
its inhabitants.

627
00:58:08,987 --> 00:58:11,820
It's as detailed as any
I've ever encountered.

628
00:58:12,782 --> 00:58:14,113
What do we do?

629
00:58:14,242 --> 00:58:16,528
I'd like to try her on a
stronger medication, for a start.

630
00:58:16,620 --> 00:58:18,827
I'll ask her doctor in LA to
send me a copy of her charts.

631
00:58:18,914 --> 00:58:20,870
You call my office,
make another appointment.

632
00:58:20,957 --> 00:58:21,946
Okay, great.

633
00:58:22,042 --> 00:58:24,249
Meanwhile, I'll give you
something to help her sleep.

634
00:58:25,545 --> 00:58:27,706
(HORNS BLARING)

635
00:58:31,510 --> 00:58:33,842
I'm going to be late.
I can't believe it.

636
00:58:33,929 --> 00:58:35,260
If we don't get the
extension on this loan,

637
00:58:35,347 --> 00:58:36,803
we're not going to get the
paintings or the furniture

638
00:58:36,890 --> 00:58:38,755
back on time.

639
00:58:38,850 --> 00:58:39,930
(GROANS)

640
00:58:40,018 --> 00:58:42,225
We forgot the invitations
for the historical society.

641
00:58:42,312 --> 00:58:45,679
Maybe we should just
postpone the dinner.

642
00:58:45,941 --> 00:58:47,522
<i>Kim,
it's Architectural Digest.</i>

643
00:58:47,651 --> 00:58:49,232
We have to get
the house on the cover.

644
00:58:49,319 --> 00:58:50,354
- I know.
- If we don't,

645
00:58:50,445 --> 00:58:51,776
I'm never going to
get my career back,

646
00:58:51,863 --> 00:58:53,194
and we're not going
to sell the place.

647
00:58:53,281 --> 00:58:54,316
How often have we
talked about this?

648
00:58:54,407 --> 00:58:55,522
What about
what's been happening?

649
00:58:55,617 --> 00:58:57,027
Harris?
That was an accident.

650
00:58:57,118 --> 00:58:58,608
I'm talking
about Sally.

651
00:58:58,745 --> 00:59:00,201
It's all in her head!

652
00:59:00,288 --> 00:59:02,574
It's real to her. It
doesn't matter if we see it.

653
00:59:02,666 --> 00:59:03,655
(HONKING)

654
00:59:03,750 --> 00:59:05,581
- Come on!
- Calm down!

655
00:59:06,836 --> 00:59:09,999
I'm going to walk. It'll be
faster. I'll see you back at home.

656
00:59:33,863 --> 00:59:36,479
I'm not sure how
lucid he'll be.

657
00:59:36,575 --> 00:59:38,156
He's pretty
heavily sedated.

658
00:59:39,869 --> 00:59:42,986
(MONITOR BEEPING)

659
01:00:10,358 --> 01:00:13,191
Mr. Harris, I know this is difficult,

660
01:00:13,862 --> 01:00:16,194
but I need to
understand something.

661
01:00:16,865 --> 01:00:19,823
I need to know what Sally
saw so that I can help her.

662
01:00:21,369 --> 01:00:25,362
Is she out
of the house?

663
01:00:26,249 --> 01:00:27,238
No.

664
01:00:29,753 --> 01:00:30,868
Out.

665
01:00:31,755 --> 01:00:34,872
She needs to be
out of there.

666
01:00:37,218 --> 01:00:38,253
Why?

667
01:00:42,223 --> 01:00:44,214
Why was that
room sealed up?

668
01:00:47,729 --> 01:00:50,015
Grandfather.

669
01:00:50,106 --> 01:00:53,223
Your grandfather
closed it up?

670
01:00:53,526 --> 01:00:55,062
- Yes.
- Why?

671
01:00:57,113 --> 01:00:58,228
After...

672
01:01:00,241 --> 01:01:01,230
After...

673
01:01:04,954 --> 01:01:06,160
After what?

674
01:01:08,333 --> 01:01:09,413
Blackwood.

675
01:01:11,961 --> 01:01:13,371
What about Blackwood?

676
01:01:15,924 --> 01:01:20,759
Lot 1134.

677
01:01:21,930 --> 01:01:23,761
Public library.

678
01:01:25,725 --> 01:01:30,059
<i>HARRIS: Get her out
of the house.</i>

679
01:01:32,107 --> 01:01:34,644
(SKITTERING)

680
01:01:58,633 --> 01:02:01,966
<i>WOMAN ON PA: The library
will be closing in 15 minutes.</i>

681
01:02:02,137 --> 01:02:06,471
<i>The library will be closing in 15 minutes.
Thank you.</i>

682
01:02:08,351 --> 01:02:09,431
Excuse me.

683
01:02:11,187 --> 01:02:12,222
Can I help you?

684
01:02:12,355 --> 01:02:13,390
I'm looking
for the librarian.

685
01:02:16,276 --> 01:02:17,311
Lot 1134.

686
01:02:19,654 --> 01:02:22,487
Emerson Blackwood, Special
Collections. One sec.

687
01:02:28,413 --> 01:02:29,744
Right this way.

688
01:02:48,850 --> 01:02:51,933
Can't remember the last time anyone
requested these. They're beautiful.

689
01:02:52,020 --> 01:02:54,477
I'm a designer. I've been
working at Fallen Mill.

690
01:02:54,564 --> 01:02:57,021
Wow. Now,
that's a privilege.

691
01:02:57,734 --> 01:03:01,067
Personally, I think Emerson
Blackwood rivaled Audubon.

692
01:03:02,530 --> 01:03:03,861
Come across
his mural?

693
01:03:04,699 --> 01:03:06,189
A mural? Where?

694
01:03:06,284 --> 01:03:08,445
There in the house,
supposedly.

695
01:03:08,536 --> 01:03:09,776
If you do,
I'd love to see it.

696
01:03:11,748 --> 01:03:14,080
(SALLY HUMMING)

697
01:03:45,365 --> 01:03:46,354
Hello?

698
01:04:05,969 --> 01:04:09,678
Now, it's pretty
ironic, really.

699
01:04:09,764 --> 01:04:11,595
For a committed realist,

700
01:04:11,683 --> 01:04:14,470
someone who insisted on
drawing only from nature,

701
01:04:14,811 --> 01:04:16,802
to do these at
the end of his life.

702
01:04:16,896 --> 01:04:18,227
I've looked at everything by Blackwood,

703
01:04:18,314 --> 01:04:19,850
and I've never
seen any of these.

704
01:04:19,941 --> 01:04:22,683
You wouldn't. The family
made it a restricted donation.

705
01:04:22,777 --> 01:04:24,233
These may never
be published.

706
01:04:24,320 --> 01:04:25,480
Is it possible
to get copies?

707
01:04:27,031 --> 01:04:28,942
I'll see what I can do.

708
01:04:29,158 --> 01:04:31,570
"Wrinkles, claws,
teeth?"

709
01:04:32,453 --> 01:04:34,159
Have you ever
read Machen?

710
01:04:34,455 --> 01:04:36,286
Arthur Machen. Welsh.

711
01:04:36,749 --> 01:04:38,455
He believed
in fairy folk,

712
01:04:38,543 --> 01:04:42,661
these ancient entities from the
netherworld, predating mankind.

713
01:04:42,922 --> 01:04:45,163
Blackwood quotes
him extensively.

714
01:04:45,258 --> 01:04:46,998
Here, that line. There.

715
01:04:47,302 --> 01:04:49,133
"One life must
be taken."

716
01:04:49,304 --> 01:04:51,215
These creatures had
to take one human life

717
01:04:51,306 --> 01:04:54,013
every time they emerged
to replenish their ranks.

718
01:04:54,100 --> 01:04:56,307
Many of these creatures
fed on the bones,

719
01:04:56,394 --> 01:04:58,385
the teeth of
young children.

720
01:04:58,771 --> 01:05:01,808
And then there's a truce,
a pact of sorts,

721
01:05:01,900 --> 01:05:04,061
between Pope Sylvester II
and these ancient beings

722
01:05:04,152 --> 01:05:05,983
in the year 999.

723
01:05:06,821 --> 01:05:08,527
In exchange
for human teeth,

724
01:05:08,615 --> 01:05:11,072
they start leaving silver
pieces under the pillow.

725
01:05:18,333 --> 01:05:22,497
Now, this is the last known
drawing by Emerson Blackwood,

726
01:05:23,254 --> 01:05:27,167
made shortly before his disappearance
and the loss of his child.

727
01:05:27,884 --> 01:05:29,090
His child?

728
01:05:29,385 --> 01:05:32,422
Blackwood's only
son vanished, lost.

729
01:05:32,513 --> 01:05:36,222
Not long after, Blackwood himself
disappeared without a trace.

730
01:06:00,708 --> 01:06:01,697
No!

731
01:06:03,044 --> 01:06:04,830
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

732
01:06:11,386 --> 01:06:12,796
- (SALLY SCREAMS)
- (CREATURE SHRIEKS)

733
01:06:14,472 --> 01:06:16,383
(HISSING)

734
01:06:18,893 --> 01:06:20,008
(SALLY SCREAMING)

735
01:06:25,400 --> 01:06:27,436
(SNARLING)

736
01:06:31,406 --> 01:06:32,395
(GASPING)

737
01:06:32,573 --> 01:06:33,562
(SCREECHING)

738
01:06:33,866 --> 01:06:34,855
(SNARLING)

739
01:06:35,243 --> 01:06:36,528
No!

740
01:06:36,619 --> 01:06:38,951
No! Please!

741
01:06:39,414 --> 01:06:40,403
(SCREAMING)

742
01:06:44,961 --> 01:06:45,950
(SNARLING)

743
01:06:50,883 --> 01:06:51,872
(SCREAMING)

744
01:06:54,220 --> 01:06:55,505
SALLY: No!

745
01:07:05,148 --> 01:07:06,934
(SALLY SCREAMING)

746
01:07:09,610 --> 01:07:10,816
Sally!

747
01:07:11,112 --> 01:07:12,602
Sally, what's wrong?

748
01:07:13,573 --> 01:07:15,404
Sally, open the door!

749
01:07:16,701 --> 01:07:17,736
(GROWLING)

750
01:07:18,536 --> 01:07:19,992
(CRYING)

751
01:07:21,289 --> 01:07:22,620
(SNARLS)

752
01:07:23,332 --> 01:07:24,321
(SCREECHING)

753
01:07:25,626 --> 01:07:26,957
Oh, my God!

754
01:07:29,964 --> 01:07:32,171
Oh, oh.

755
01:07:32,258 --> 01:07:33,623
- (PANICKED BREATHING)
- Shh.

756
01:07:39,891 --> 01:07:42,098
(BREATHING RAPIDLY) Dear,
thank goodness you're home.

757
01:07:42,268 --> 01:07:44,634
- Where is she?
- I put her to bed.

758
01:07:44,812 --> 01:07:46,552
She wouldn't
stop screaming.

759
01:07:58,326 --> 01:07:59,486
Sally?

760
01:08:24,811 --> 01:08:25,800
(GRUNTS)

761
01:08:27,688 --> 01:08:29,849
(CHILD FAINTLY CRYING)

762
01:08:41,911 --> 01:08:42,991
ALEX: Kim!

763
01:08:44,080 --> 01:08:45,160
She's not down here.

764
01:08:45,414 --> 01:08:47,905
I think she's run away.
She's done it before.

765
01:08:50,461 --> 01:08:52,292
